column168: ONE DRUM CAME INTO 181 ON TRAILER #50-389 FROM 18.  DRUM WAS LEAKING FROM A SMALL HOLE IN THE BOTTOM.  DRUM WAS PUT INTO SALVAGE DRUM.  VERY LITTLE PRODUCT LOSS.

THIS TANK CAR WAS FOUND WITH SLIGHT SPILLAGE OF PRODUCT AROUND SAFETY VENT.  BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND FAILED FRANGIBLE DISK.  A REPLACEMENT WAS INSTALLED AND THE CAR WAS WIPED CLEAN, THEN RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION TO THE FINAL DESTINATION.  THE FRANGIBLE DISK WAS RATED FOR 100 PSI.
A DRUM OF RESIN SOLUTION, A CLASS 3 LIQUID, WAS DAMAGED BY WHAT APPEARED TO BE A FORK BLADE.  THE DRUM WAS CRACKED WITH MINIMAL LEAKAGE.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: ON ARRIVAL AT PRESTON'S FALLS CREEK TERMINAL, DRUMS OF PAINT, A CLASS 3 LIQUID, WERE FOUND LEAKING FROM AROUND THE TOP LID AREA.  IT APPEARED TO BE DEFECTIVE LID SEALS.  THE LEAKAGE WAS MINIMAL AND CLEANED UP AT THE TERMINAL.  THE LIDS WERE RESEALED AND THE SHIPMENT DELIVERED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: WHILE LOADING TRUCK, AN OUTAGE OCCURRED WHICH WAS CONTAINED, CLEANED UP AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.

UPON COMPLETION OF UNLOADING TRAILER, THE DRIVER CLOSED THE HEADER VALVE, CAUSING THE TRANSFER HOSE TO OVERPRESSURE AND FAIL.  THE DRIVER SHUTDOWN HIS PUMP AND DRAINED RESIDUAL PRODUCT INTO A BUCKET.  TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS LIKE THIS, TRAINING WILL BE DONE WITH EMPLOYEES TO INSURE PROPER PROCEDURES ARE FOLLOWED.

THE DRIVER WAS LOADING CRUDE FROM A LEASE STORAGE TANK.  HIS PUMP WAS INADVERTENTLY REVERSED SO WHEN HE SHUT THE HEADER VALVE, THE TRANSFER HOSE OVERPRESSURED AND FAILED.  THE NECESSARY CLEANUP WAS HANDLED.  TO PREVENT FUTURE ACCIDENTS LIKE THIS, A GUARD WILL BE PLACED AROUND LOAD LEVER.

CSE D/SR GLYNN BUFFINGTON WAS UNLOADING 55 GALLON DRUM WITH DOCK DRUM TRUCKS.  WHEN HE WENT TO PUSH DRUM TRUCKS UNDER DRUM, DRUM TRUCK SLIPPED CAUSING METAL WEDGE OF DRUM TRUCK TO PUNCTURE BOTTOM OF DRUM.  DRUM WAS TURNED OVER IMMEDIATELY AND PLACED IN OVERPACK DRUM.  ABSORBENT WAS USED TO CLEAN UP SPILL THAT HADN'T EVAPORATED AND ABSORBENT WAS PLACED IN WASTE RECOVERY DRUM FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO USE MORE CAUTION AND TO USE TOOLS PROPERLY WHEN HANDLING ANY DRUM PRODUCT.
DRIVER UNLOADING AT CONSIGNEE AND HOSES DEVELOPED LEAK.  ONE LENGTH HAD A PIN HOLE IN IT AND THE OTHER LEAKED AT THE FITTING.  USED ABSORBENTS TO CLEAN UP SPILL.

DRIVER WAS UNLOADING (USING PUMP) INTO AND ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK. STORAGE TANK OVERFILLED SPILLING DIESEL FUEL ONTO CONCRETE PARKING LOT AND INSIDE CONTAINMENT AREA.  CLARK ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CALLED OUT TO CLEAN UP SPILL.  CUSTOMER SHOULD ORDER ONLY AMOUNT THAT WILL FIT IN STORAGE TANK.
ONE DRUM BEGAN TO LEAK FROM A HOLE IN BOTTOM OF DRUM.  DRUM WAS OVERPACKED. SPILL WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT AND PUT IN OVERPACK WITH LEAKING DRUM.

AS TRAIN CREW WAS PASSING THEIR TRAIN IN LOCOMOTIVES ON AJACENT TRACK TO GO TO REAR END, THEY DETECTED AN ODOR OF CHLORINE AND REPORTED IT TO THE YARD MASTER.  A RESPONSE TEAM FROM BORDEN CHEMICAL WAS CALLED FOR AND ARRIVED 2100 HOURS.  RESPONSE TEAM REPLACED PACKING AROUND ANGLE VALVE AND RELEASED CAR BACK TO TRANSPORTATION.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: DURING A ROUTINE SWITCHING OPERATIONS, A TRASNPORTATION EMPLOYEE OBSERVED WHAT WAS LATER DETERMINED AS PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET AREA OF CELX 3213.  CAR WAS RELOCATED TO AN ISOLATED AREA AND THE TRACK SECURED.  A CONTAINER WAS POSITIONED UNDER CAR FOR CONTAINMENT OF LEAKAGE. AN IN-DEPTH INSPECTION REVEALED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM BOTTOM PLATE, ADJACENT TO BOTTOM OUTLET.  THIS PLATE IS APPROXIMATELY 10-12" IN CIRCUMFERENCE, FASTENED TO TANK SHELL WITH 12 BOLTS.  SLIGHT LEAKAGE APPEARED TO BE COMING FROM BETWEEN PLATE AND TANK SHELL AS WELL AS TWO BOLTS HOLES.  SEVERAL ATTEMPTS AT TIGHTENING THE BOLTS FAILED TO STOP LEAKAGE, THUS REQUIRING TRANSLOADING OF CAR.

SWITCH CREW DETECTED SMALL VAPOR LEAK FROM SIDE OF TANK CAR ACAX 080010 AND REPORTED IT TO YARD MASTER.  TRAINMASTER HAD CAR MOVED TO ISOLATED AREA ON TRASH TRACK.  CHEMTREC NOTIFIED, NRC NOTIFIED, AND 911 CALLED FOR MEMPHIS FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZ-MAT TEAM.  SHIPPER SENT HAZ MAT TEAM FROM BATON ROUGE, LA AND ALSO CALLED FOR EM-TECH OUT OF HOUSTON, TX.  SHELBY COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGAMENT CALLED FOR 1/2 MILE EVACUATION OF AREA UNTIL LEAK COULD BE STOPPED AND PRODUCT COULD BE TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TANK CAR. LEAK WAS STOPPED AT 1:20AM ON APRIL 3 AND TRANSFER WORK WAS COMPLETED AT 3:00AM ON APRIL 4, 1997.

DRIVER SOUTHBOUND ON INDIANAPOLIS BLVD., RT. 41, IN E. CHICAGO, IN AT ROXANNA DRIVE, UNDER SOUTHSHORE RR OVERPASS, WHEN TRAFFIC LIGHT CHANGED. DRIVER HAD TO STOP QUICK WHICH CAUSED THE RUPTURE DISC TO BLOW RELEASING 10 TO 20 GALLONS OF SPENT ACID ONTO THE LEFT LANE.  E. CHICAGO FIRE DEPT. RESPONDED AND COVERED THE SPILL WITH SODA ASH TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPENT ACID, THEN SWEPT IT UP AND PUT INTO DRUMS TO RETURN TO THEIR PLANT FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  THE FIRE DEPT. WASHED DOWN THE AREA.  ALSO, NATIONAL RESPONSE WAS CALLED BECAUSE RT. 41 WAS CLOSED DOWN FOR 2 1/2 HOURS FOR CLEANUP.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: DURING THE SORT THE BOX WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING PAINT.  THE BOX WAS REMOVED FROM THE SORT AND PLACED IN A HEAVY MIL PLASTIC BAG.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED THIS MORNING.  I SPOKE TO DOUGLAS GRAHAM.  I REQUESTED MSDS FOR THE PAINT.  I HAVE SINCE RECEIVED THE MSDS AND FOUND THAT OF THE THREE CANS OF PAINT, TWO HAVE A FLASHPOINT OF 41 DEGREES F.  THAT, AND COUPLED WITH THE AEROSOLS, WE BELIEVE TO HAVE AN UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS.  AT THAT POINT I NOTIFIED ALEX EVANS WITH THE NASHVILLE FAA CASFO.  THE FREIGHT IS BEING HELD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS, OR OTHER INDICATORS THAT WOULD HAVE LED US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.  THIS IS AN UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOOD.

DRIVER PICKED UP FOUR TOTES IN MINE HILL, NJ, DRIVER PERFORMED ROUTINE TIRE CHECK TO VEHICLE AND VISUALLY CHECKED THE TOTES.  DRIVER ARRIVED TO PICK UP BALANCE OF HIS LOAD IN WILMINGTON, DE.  UPON OPENING THE DOORS TO THE TRAILER, THE DRIVER IDENTIFIED THAT ONE OF THE TOTES HAD RELEASED MATERIAL UNDER PRESSURE ONTO THE TRAILER.  THE RELEASE RESULTED FROM A PLUG BEING LODGED IN THE TOP OF THE TOTE.  THE MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP BY A RESPONSE TEAM WHICH ALSO REPLACED THE PLUG.  THE TOTE WAS THEN DELIVERED TO THE DESIGNATED TSDF.

AT SHIPPERS' PLANT, DRIVER FAILED TO CLOSE THE 3/4" AIR VALVE IN DOME AREA OF TANK TRUCK AFTER LOADING.  WHEN THE UNIT LEFT THE LOADING RACK, IT SPILLED PRODUCT OUT THE OPEN VALVING UPON THE ROAD TO THE PLANT SCALE.  THE LEAKAGE WAS SEEN IMMEDIATELY AND VALVES SHUT.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP BY TOSCO REFINING CORP PERSONNEL.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES. DRIVER ERROR CAUSED THIS SPILL.  THERE WAS NO MECHANICAL FAILURE.

column168: DELIVERY LOCATION HAS TWO 4000 GALLON UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANKS WHICH ARE PIPED TOGETHER.  AFTER PUTTING SOME PRODUCT IN FIRST TANK, THE DRIVER WAS DROPPING INTO SECOND TANK WHEN THE COLLAR AND CAP CAME OFF THE FIRST TANK DUE TO PRESSURE BUILD UP.  PROBLEM WAS CAUSED BY IMPROPER INSTALLATION OF EQUIPMENT AT CUSTOMER LOCATION.  GREENWOOD FIRE DEPT RESPONDED AND TOOK EMERGENCY MEASURES TO CONTAIN SPILL.  CLEAN-UP AND REMOVAL WAS DONE BY PETROLEUM WORKS, 115 GULF ST., GREENWOOD, SC  29648.

THE LTC DRIVER HAD HOOKED UP HIS HOSES AND STARTED THE OFF LOADING.  HE HAD A REVERSIBLE PTO AND WAS PUSHING THE PRODUCT OUT OF THE TOP OF THE TANK INSTEAD OF OUT OF THE HOSE.  WE CONTRACTED THE CLEAN UP WITH HAZ CON AND TEXARKANA, ARK.

column168: THIS UNDELIVERD SHPT WAS ON A TRLR 207662 THAT HAD TO BE DROPPED AT ANOTHER SHPR.  UPON ARRVIAL AT THAT SHPR, FRT (3 DRUMS) WERE TRANSFERRED OFF OF SKID ON TO FLOOR OF TRLR (205820) THAT WAS BEING P/U.  AN EMPTY PALELT WAS PUT UPRIGHT BETWEEN THE DRUM AND FRT NEXT TO IT.  UPON ARRVIAL BACK AT SL TERM, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT 1 DRUM HAD SLID INTO "CORNER" OF SHARP METAL GRATE WHICH PUT A GASH APPX 1 1/2" W X 1/8" H ON SIDE OF DRUM APPX 4" UP FROM BOTTOM.  DAMAGED DRUM WAS TAKEN OFF OF TRLR, SEALED WITH DUCT TAPE & STORED IN SAFE AREA.  TRLR WAS REMOVED FROM DOCK (AFTER ABSORBENT COMPOUND WAS PLACED ON THE SPILL) & PARKED IN THE YARD, WHERE IT WAS CLEANED OUT THE NEXT MORNING.  THE COMPOUND THAT ABSORBED THE SPILL IS IN A RECOVERY DRUM TO BE SENT TO SALVAGE.  THE CONSIGNEE WILL ACCEPT DELIVERY OF THE DAMAGED DRUM INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM.

EQUIPMENT FAILURE DURING OFF LOADING PROCESS.  THE COTTER KEY CAME OUT OF THE STEM ALLOWING THE NUT TO WORK LOOSE AND THE STEM TO COME OUT.  WHEN THE VALVE WAS OPENED PRODUCT FORCED THE VALVE OUT SPILLING APPX 2 GALLONS.

column168: AT SHIPPERS' PLANT, DRIVER FAILED TO CLOSE THE BLEEDER VALVE IN DOME AREA OF TANK TRUCK AFTER LOADING.  WHEN THE UNIT LEFT THE LOADING RACK, IT SPILLED PRODUCT OUT THE OPEN VALVING UPON CLIMBING HILL INSIDE THE PLANT. LEAKAGE WAS SEEN  IMMEDIATELY, AND VALVES SHUT.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP BY GENERAL CHEMICAL CORP PERSONNEL.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES. DRIVER ERROR CAUSED THIS SPILL.  THERE WAS NO MECHANICAL FAILURE.

column168: THIS LOADED TANK CAR WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING PRODUCT DURING CLASSIFICATION.  THE CAR WAS TAKEN TO AN ISOLATION AREA AND HAD BUCKETS PLACED BELOW THE AREA WHERE THE LEAKAGE WAS EVIDENT.  ALL MANWAY BOLTS WERE LOOSE, AND TOP LEAKAGE STOPPED WHEN THESE WERE TIGHTENED.  BNSF RESPONDERS DETERMINED LOCATION OF LEAK TO BE BETWEEN THE TANK FLANGE AND THE BOTTOM OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  THE EXACT CAUSE OF THE LEAKAGE WAS NOT OBTAINED DUE TO THIS AREA BEING PARTIALLY COVERED BY THE BOTTOM SKID PROTECTION FLARINGS.  THE CAUSE IS BELIEVED TO BE A FAILED GASKET.  PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO FOUR TANK TRUCKS FOR DELIVERY TO THE CONSIGNEE. CONTAINED PRODUCT WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER (ABOUT 10 GALLONS).  CAR WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER'S FACILITY AT LONGVIEW, TX.  INBOUND TRAIN: H-SRBA1-07

column168: ON 4/19/97 WE PICKED UP A VAN TRAILER LOADED WITH DRUMS FROM A HOUSEHOLD HAZARDOUS WASTE DAY COLLECTION SITE AND BROUGHT IT BACK TO OUR TRUCKING FACILITY.  THE LOAD WAS SCHEDULED FOR DELIVERY TO THE DISPOSAL FACILITY ON 4/22/97.  WHEN OUR DRIVER HOOKED UP TO THE TRAILER ON 4/22/97, HE NOTICED THAT THE GROUND BENEATH THE MID SECTION OF THE TRAILER WAS STAINED.  UPON OPENING THE REAR DOOR OF THE TRAILER A DRUM WAS SPOTTED WITH A LID POPPED UP AT A 45 DEGREE ANGLE.  THROUGH AIR MONITORING IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE TRAILER COULD BE ENTERED SAFELY.  THE DRUM IN QUESTION IS A CONSOLIDATED DRUM OF WASTES FROM A HOUSEHOLD HAZARDOUS WASTE DAY EVENT. PRELIMINARY INVESTIGATION INDICATES THAT THE DRUM WAS A CONSOLIDATION OF GASOLINE, OILS AND PAINTS.  THERE MUST ALSO HAVE BEEN A FOAM SEALANT OF ICOCYANATE ORIGIN CONSOLIDATED IN THE DRUM.  A REACTION CAUSING POLYMERIZATION OCCURRED WHICH RESULTED IN SOLIDIFICATION OF THE CONTENTS CREATING INTERNAL PRESSURE FORCING THE LID OF THE DRUM TO POP OPEN.  THE POLYMERIZATION CAUSED APPX 10 GALLONS OF THE REMAINING LIQUID TO BE FORCED OUT OF THE DRUM.  THE CONTAMINATED STONE AND GRAVEL FROM BENEATH THE TRAILER WAS EXCAVATED TO A DEPTH BELOW THE STAINING.  THE SPILL CLEAN UP MATERIAL WAS MANIFESTED AND THEN TAKEN TO A HAZ WASTE TREATMENT FACILITY WHERE IT WILL BE DISPOSED ACCORDING TO ALL STATE AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS.

column168: A VACUUM TRAILER WAS DISPATCHED TO U.S. AIR GROUP, INC. IN ORDER TO LOAD A SHIPMENT OF PETROLEUM OIL FOR TRANSPORTATION TO MURPHYS WASTE OIL SERVICES, INC. A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WAS ENROUTE FROM TBG COGEN TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC.  DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE, INC. IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE TOP LID OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND OVERPACKED THE LEAKING CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL DEBRIS GENERATED FROM THE CLEAN UP AND DECONTAMINATION  OF THE FLOOR WAS PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM AND WAS DISPOSED OF AT THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING PAPER.  A REVIEW OF THE LEAKING CONTAINER INDICATED THAT THE GASKET USED AT THE TOP CLOSURE OF THE CONTAINER WAS DEFECTIVE ALLOWING THE MATERIAL TO ESCAPE FROM THE CONTAINER.

THIS SHIPMENT LEAKED IN OUR SYSTEM.  UPON INSPECTION BY OUR FEDEX DG/SPILL SPECIALIST IT APPEARED THAT THE INNER CONTENTS HAD LEAKED THROUGH THE PLASTIC BAG.  THERE WAS A PART WRAPPED IN BUBBLEWRAP AND SOME SORT OF CUSHIONING MATERIAL WHICH DID NOT APPEAR TO BE ABSORBING THE CONTENTS. THE PLASTIC BAG HAD TWO TIES ON TOP.  THE EMPLOYEE REPORTED THAT THE PACKAGE SMELLED LIKE KEROSENE.  I CONTACTED THE SHIPPER AND WE HELD THE PACKAGE UNTIL THE MSDS COULD BE FAX'D TO US.  IT WAS "KEROSENE" PER THE MSDS.  I PHONED F.A.A. AGENT JIM WISEMAN AT (310)215-2280 TO REPORT THE UNDECLARED.  HOWEVER, SINCE THE SHIPMENT WAS OUTBOUND FREIGHT AND HAD THUS FAR BEEN TRUCKED NOT TRANSPORTED BY AIRCRAFT, MR. WISEMAN INDICATED THAT THE F.A.A. WOULD NOT BE CONDUCTING AN INVESTIGATION.  I THEN CONTACTED THE SHIPPER TO INFORM THEM THE SHIPMENT COULD BE PICKED UP BY THEM.

THE LAIDLAW DRIVER PICKED UP A VACUUM BOX LOAD OF LEADED TANK BOTTOMS AT BASIS PETROLEUM, INC. (CUSTOMER) IN KROTZ SPRINGS, LA.  THE VACUUM BOX WAS INSPECTED FOR TRANSPORTATION AND WAS TRANSPORTED TO CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT, INC. IN PORT ARTHUR, TX.  THE LOAD WAS SAMPLED AND TAKEN TO THE STORAGE AREA FOR OFF-LOADING.  WHEN THE LAIDLAW DRIVER STARTED TO SET THE BOX DOWN IN THE STORAGE AREA, MATERIAL STARTED TO COME OUT OF THE BOX. THE BOX WAS IMMEDIATELY BROUGHT BACK ONTO THE TRAILER.  WHEN THE LAIDLAW DRIVER WENT TO INSPECT THE REAR OF THE BOX, HE SAW THAT THE CAM-LOCK ON THE CAP HAD BROKEN WHILE HE WAS UNLOADING THE BOX.  THE AREA IN WHICH THE MATERIAL SPILLED WAS IN A SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AREA. ******************* THE VACUUM BOX HAD BEEN LEASED BY THE CONTRACTOR OF THE CUSTOMER FROM ANOTHER VENDOR.  THE BOX WAS LOADED BY A CONTRACTOR OF THE CUSTOMER.  THIS VACUUM BOX HAS TWO OPENINGS, BOTH SITUATED AT THE TOP OF THE OX, ONE ON THE FRONT AND ONE ON THE REAR.  THE TOP FITTING HAD BEEN FITTED WITH A CAM-LOCK.  THE BOX DID NOT HAVE A SECONDARY VALVE ON THIS CAM-LOCK FITTING.  IT JUST HAD A FITTING AT THE END OF THE HOSE FITTING AND A CAM-LOCK ON THE FITTING.  THE CAM-LOCK BROKE AND CAUSED THE CAP TO POP OFF THE FITTING. ******************************** PERSONNEL AT CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT SECURED THE CAM-LOCK BACK ONTO THE BOX WITH DUCT TAPE.  THE VACUUM BOX AND SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AREA WAS CLEANED AND THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS COLLECTED BY CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT FOR DISPOSAL.  AS PART OF OUR CORRECTIVE ACTION, ADDITIONAL TRAINING HAS BEEN PROVIDED TO OUR DRIVERS (SINCE THE INCIDENT) ON HOW TO INSPECT VACUUM BOXES AND CONTAINERS CORRECTLY.  THIS WILL BE REVIEWED ON QUARTERLY BASIS IN OUR DRIVERS MEETINGS.  WE WILL ALSO NOTIFY CUSTOMERS OF PROPER PACKAGING FOR VACUUM BOXES.

column168: TANK CAR ACFX 81561 WAS DISCOVERED VENTING THROUGH THE SAFETY VALVE AROUND 12.15 A.M. ON APRIL 11, 1997. PERSONNEL FROM THE RAILROAD, FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND HUNTSMAN CHEMICAL CORPORATION RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. EFFORTS WERE MADE TO COOL THE CONTENTS BY RUNNING CARBON DIOXIDE, REFRIGERATED LIQUID, THROUGH THE INTERIOR HEATER COIL PIPING. THIS WAS DISCONTINUED BECAUSE OF PROBLEMS WITH EXCESSIVE PRESSURE IN THE PIPING. A PRESSURE GAUGE WAS CONNECTED TO THE VAPOR VALVE UNDER THE TOP PROTECTIVE COVER, AND IT WAS FOUND THAT THE PRESSURE INSIDE THE TANK WAS 20 PSI. A SMALL AMOUNT OF VAPORS WERE STILL ESCAPING FROM A SECOND VAPOR VALUE MOUNTED ON THE TOP THE MANWAY. A DECISION WAS MADE TO MOVE THE CAR TO THE HUNTSMAN CHEMICAL PLANT. A SPECIAL TRAIN WAS MADE UP AND TANK CAR WAS MOVED TO THE PLANT, A DISTANCE OF ABOUT ONE MILE, THE CAR WAS PLACED IN THE PLANT ABOUT 7:00 P.M. ON APRIL 11, 1997. AT THE PLANT, HUNTSMAN PERSONNEL WERE TO FURTHER HANDLE THE CAR TO REMOVE THE CONTENTS. DURING THE INCIDENT THERE WAS NOT A FULL EVACUATION OF THE AREA. IT IS AN INDUSTRIAL AREA WITH FEW RESIDENCES, BUT PEOPLE WERE NOT ALLOWED TO ENTER OR LEAVE THE AREA. ** HUNTSMAN CHEMICAL PERSONNEL INDICATED THAT THE LOAD POLYMERIZED. THEY ESTIMATED THAT ABOUT 25% OF THE LOAD WAS LOST DURING THE VENTING. WHILE THE CAR WAS VENTING THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS SPRAYING WATER ON THE ESCAPING VAPORS, TO REDUCE THE CHANCE OF THE VAPORS TRAVELING TO AN IGNITION SOURCE. AN INITIAL EXAMINATION OF THE CAR INDICATES THAT IT WAS NOT DAMAGED BY THE HEAT AND PRESSURES GENERATED DURING THE POLYMERIZATION PROCESS. THE TANK CAR, ACFX 81561, IS A 111A100WI BUILT IN JANUARY 1965. IT HAS A FULL CENTER SILL, IS JACKETED WITH INTERIOR HEATER COILS. THE TANK, COILS, AND SAFETY VALVE WERE LAST TESTED IN 1993. THE REASON THE LOAD POLYMERIED HAS NOT BEEN DETERMINED.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 4:30 AM, OUR DRIVER WAS ENROUTE WITH A FULL LOAD OF GASOLINE (8,500 GALLONS) TO A CUSTOMER. AT APPX 16:20 THE CREW NOTIFIED THE YARDMASTER OF A DERAILED TANK CAR, GATX 66340,, AND A LIQUID LEAKING FROM A PUNCTURE OF SAME. THE DISPATCHERS OFFICE NOTIFIED THE FOLLOWING AGENCIES:  STATE OF ILLINOIS DEPT OF TRANSPORTATION; STATE OF ILLINOIS EMA; FRA NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER.  FOAM WAS APPLIED TO THE SPILL AT 9:40 PM AND PRODUCT RECOVERY STARTED AT APPROXIMATELY 4:35 AM. THE GATEWAY WESTERN WILL CONTINUE TO HAVE SAFETY MEETINGS, SAFETY TRAINING AND THE RULE COMPLIANCE BY EFFICIENCY TESTING AND RULES CHECKS.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 12:00 NOON, APRIL 25, 1997, A TRANSFER HOSE FITTING FAILED CAUSING 20-50 GALLONS OF DILUTE (16-18% HCL; 82-84% H20) HYDROCHLORIC ACID SOLUTION TO SPILL ONTO SOIL AT THE PVI FACILITY AT 3209 GAVEZ ST., FORT WORTH, TX.  THE VACUUM TRAILER DRIVER STOPPED THE LEAK WITHIN 30 SECONDS.  THE RELEASE AFFECTED AN AREA APPROXIMATELY 20' BY 80'; THERE WERE NO EMISSIONS TO THE AIR OR WATER.  IMMEDIATED ACTIONS TAKEN TO CLEAN UP THE RELEASE INCLUDED USING THE VACUUM TRUCK TO REMOVE ALL STANDING LIQUID ON TOP OF THE SOIL.  ON WEDNESDAY, APRIL 30, A RTS SUPERVISOR WENT TO THE SPILL SITE WITH A LOCAL REMEDIATION CONTRACTOR (EMC HAZMAT) TO REMOVE CONTAMINATED SOIL.  THEY EXCAVATED AN AVERAGE OF 4" OF SOIL OVER THE AFFECTED AREA.  BECAUSE THE ONLY HAZARD ASSOCIATED WITH THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CORROSIVITY (D002), DEPRESSED SOIL PH WAS CHOSEN AS AN INDICATOR OF CONTAMINATION.  SAMPLES WERE TAKEN OF THE SOIL UNDERLYING THE EXCAVATED MATERIAL AND COMPARED WITH A BACKGROUND (CLEAN) SAMPLE. BOTH SAMPLES SHOWED PH BETWEEN 6 AND 7.  THE AREA WAS THEN BACKFILLED WITH NEW SOIL.

column168: ON 4/10/97 A SPILL WAS REPORTED.  THE LOCATION OF THE SPILL WAS ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH 45177, AT OUR HAZ MAT SORT FACILITY.  HAZ MAT COORDINATOR, ADDIE CAMPTON AND SPILL TECH SHELLY MORGAN RESPONDED.  UPON OUR INVESTIGATION, WE DISCOVERED  A  FIBERBOARD EMITTING AN ODOR.  THE OUTER BOX WAS MARKED (MOTOR SPIRIT, UN1203, FLAMMABLE LIQUID, CARGO AIRCRAFT ONLY).  THE INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS WERE AS FOLLOWS:  2 METAL RECEPTACLES WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURE, ONE OF WHICH WAS CRACKED  THE RECEPTACLES CONTAINED APPX 1 (ONE) LITER EACH OF MOTOR SPIRITS.  THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR THIS RECEPTACLE LEAKING WAS FAILURE OF THE  CLOUSRE, DUE TO IT BEING CRACKED.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND CONTAINED THE PROPER HAZ MAT CERTIFICATIONS TO FORWARD THE SHIPMENT TO ITS DESTINATION.

column168: DRIVER UNLOADING AT CONSIGNEE DOCK WHEN HE DISCOVERED FLUID PUDDLE ON FLOOR. KATHERINE STRANG INFORMED HIM THAT IT WAS ONLY A 2 PERCENT SOLUTION.  THIS IS A NON-REPORTABLE QUANTITY AND THAT WE COULD CLEAN IT UP WITH FLOOR DRY. OIL TRANSPORT VEHICLE WAS USING THE TRUCK POWER TAKE OFF TO PUMP FUEL OIL THROUGH A RUBBER HOSE INTO THE FUEL TANK ON A TUG BOAT.  ON THE END (UNLOADING END) A LENGTH OF STRAIGHT PIPE WAS FASTENED TO THE END OF THE HOSE.  THIS PIPE WAS STUCK DOWN INTO THE TUG BOAT FUEL INTAKE RECEPTACLE. AN EMPLOYEE OF THE TUG BOAT WAS ASSIGNED THE RESPONSIBILITY OF HOLDING THE PIPE IN THE INTAKE.  THE TUG BOAT EMPLOYEE STATED THAT BECAUSE OF THE VERY HIGH WINDS ONE SPECIALLY LARGE WAVE STRUCK THE TUG CAUSING IT TO VIOLENTLY ROCK WHICH CAUSED HIM TO LOSE HIS BALANCE AND HE TURNED LOOSE OF THE HOSE END.  WHEN HE TURNED LOOSE, PUMPING PRESSURE CAUSED THE HOSE END TO COME OUT OF THE SHIPS INTAKE.  FUEL SPRAYED TO TOP OF THE TUG AND ABOUT TEN GALLONS WENT INTO THE WATER BEFORE THE PUMP WAS SHUT DOWN.  YOUR REFRENCE NUMBER: 384055.

AT 1020 HRS ON 4/11/97, SR SPECIAL AGENT T J BOUDREAUX WAS NOTIFIED BY AVONDALE YARDMASTER R E BAILEY THAT TANKCAR GATX 15376 WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE TOP AROUND THE VALVES.  AT 1050 HRS ON 4/11/97, AN INSPECTION OF THE TANK CAR BY AGENT BOUDREAUX REVEALED THAT THE AIR INLET VALVE PLUG WAS LOOSE.  THE PLUG WAS TIGHTENED.  IT WAS ALSO NOTED THAT PRODUCT APPEARED TO BE BYPASSING THE LIQUID DISCHARGE PIPE CAP.  AGENT BOUDREAUX PLACED A CALL TO THE SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE, CHRIS FRILOUX, SUPERINTENDENT TRANSPORTATION SPECIALIST, CYTEC INDUSTRIES.  HE ARRIVED AT 1300 HRS AND INSPECTED THE CAR.  HE NOTED THAT THE THREADS ON THE DISCHARGE PIPE WERE WORN AND DETERIORATED.  FRILOUX WENT BACK TO HIS PLANT AND AT 1500 HRS HE RETURNED WITH A CREW.  APPX 1/2 INCH OF THREADS WERE ADDED TOWARD THE BASE OF THE PIPE AND THE TOP 1/2 INCH WAS REMOVED.  PIPE TAPE WAS PLACED ON THREADS AND SODA ASH WAS SPRINKLED TO DILUTE ANY ACID ON THE TANKCAR.  IT WAS ALSO WASHED DOWN WITH WATER.   THERE WAS NO REPORT OF INJURY OR CONTAMINATION OF THE ENVIRONMENT.

column168: AT 8:15 AM, ON 4-29-97, DRIVER ROY MCDOWELL WAS HEADING EAST BOUND ON I-90 AND WAS PULLED INTO THE SCALE HOUSE AT CLE ELUM, WA FOR A ROUTINE SAFETY INSPECTION.  THE SCALE OPERATOR NOTICED LIQUID LEAKING OUT OF THE SIDE DOOR OF THE TRAILER.  THE SCALE OPERATOR INSPECTED THE BILL OF LADING AND NOTICED THE HAZ LABEL AND PROCEEDED TO NOTIFY WASHINGTON STATE PATROL. WSP THEN PROCEEDED TO NOTIFY KITTITAS FIRE DEPT AND CHEMTREC FOR ADVICE ON CONTAINING THE LEAK.  FIRE DEPT PERSONNEL ARRIVED ON SCENE AND UNDER THE ADVICE OF CHEMTREK PROCEEDED TO COVER THE SPILL WITH DIRT.  IT WAS THEN DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK WAS CAUSED BY LEAKING VENT CAPS PRODUCING APPX 1-GALLONG OF SPILLAGE.  THE DRIVER WAS THEN PUT OUT OF SERVICE BY DOT UNTIL THE PROBLEM WAS RESOLVED.  WE THEN DISPATCHED TRAINED PERSONNEL TO THE SITE WITH NEW CAPS AND VENT PLUGS TO REPLACE THE LEAKING ONES.  THE LOAD WAS THEN REINSPECTED BY THE DOT AND THE TRUCK WAS RELEASED FROM THE SCALE HOUSE AT APPX 2:00 P.M.

UMS ATTEMPTED TO CONTACT CNEE WITHOUT SUCCESS.  I NOTIFIED CHEMTREC AS PER H/L DG MFST (TRACEY JACKSON).   I NOTIFIED MATT KRYNSKI-HLA HAZMAT MGR.  I NOTIFIED H/L PHILADELPHIA (TERRY NOLAN). column168: THIS WAS AN UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPMENT CARRY ON BOARD THE AIRFACT BY THE PASSENGER.  TWENTY MINUTES INTO THE FLIGHT FROM LAX THE FLIGHT ATTENDENTS NOTICED A VERY FOUL ODOR EMITING FROM THE OVERHEAD BIN IN ROW 16.  THE SUBSTANCE HAD LEAKED FROM THE BOX AND GOTTEN ON A TENNIS RACKET THAT WAS IN THE BIN AND THE SUBSTANCE HAD DRIPPED ON TO A CUSTOMER WHO WAS SEATED BELOW THE OVERHEAD BIN.  THE FLIGHT ATTENDENT CLEANED UP THE SPILL AND PLACED THE LEAKING CONTAINER IN A PLASTIC BAG AND PLACED IT IN THE REAR LAV.  THE PASSENGER WHO CARRIED ON THE BOX WAS DETAINED AND QUESTIONED UPON ARRIVAL AT OAK.

THE PRODUCT WAS APPARENTLY UNDER NITROGEN PRESSURE BY THE CUSTOMER.  NO ONE ACTUALLY WITNESSED MR. SMITH'S FALL - BUT A NOISE LIKE AN EXPLOSION WAS HEARD AND MR. SMITH HAD FALLEN OFF THE TRUCK AND LANDED ON THE GROUND.  MR SMITH SUFFERED SEVERAL ORTHOPAEDIC TRAUMA INJURIES. CUSTOMER CLEANED UP SPILLED PROJECT.  NO INJURIES DUE TO PRODUCT.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1:30PM, APRIL 5, 1997, CARMAN BOTTS ADVISED YARDMASTER OF ODOR AND HISSING NOISE COMING FROM RAIL CAR GATX43798.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND CHEMTREC, INFOTRAC, AND SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER DISPATCHED HAZARDOUS RESPONSE CREW EMTECH AND THEY DETERMINED THAT MANWAY NEEDED TO BE TIGHTENED AND AFTER DOING SO, CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO ITS DESTINATION.  AT INITIAL INCIDENT CARMAN BOTTS FELT EYE AND SKIN IRRITATION AND WANTED NO MEDICAL ATTENTION AND WANTED TO GO HOME TO SHOWER.  LATER IN THE EVENING HE WENT TO THE EMERGENCY ROOM FOR EVALUATION AND WAS FOUND TO HAVE BRONCHITIS IRRITATION WHICH WAS A PRIOR CONDITION. MR. BOTTS WAS ABSENT FROM WORK FOR 22 DAYS.

column168: SHIPMENT WAS BEING HANDLED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE LEAKAGE OCCURED. HANDLING PERSONNEL NOTICED WETNESS AS WELL AS A HISSING NOISE COMING FROM THE INSIDE OF THE PACKAGE. THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL TWO KIDDE FIRE EXTINGUISHERS. ONE OF THE FIRE EXTINGUISHER'S VALVE STEM APPARENTLY FAILED RESULTING IN THE DISCHARGE OF THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE EXTINGUISHER INTO THE BOX. THERE WAS ALSO AN INFLATABLE LIFE RAFT IN THE BOX WITH THE CYLINDERS. THERE WERE NO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL MARKINGS OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IN EVIDENCE WITH THE SHIPMENT. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE F.A.A. FOR DISPOSITION.

O4/16/97 HAZ MAT SPILL TECHNICAN JEFF MCLAUGHLIN REPORTED A LEAKING SHIPMENT INSIDE A BUILDING OF OUR SORT FACILITY.  UPON ARRIVAL, HE FOUND A BROWN FIBREBOARD BOX SHOWING VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE. JEFF TESTED THE LIQUID, PH READING WAS NEUTRAL.  HE OPENED THE BOX FOUND A PLASTIC GALLON CONTAINER WITH A SNAP ON CLOSURE.  THE CLOSURE WAS NOT SECURE ON THE CONTAINER UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION OF THE REMAINING CONTENTS, THERE IS A PERSONAL NOTE ON "SABIN ROBBINS" COMPANY LETTERHEAD.  THE NOTE ADVISES "HERE IS A LITTLE SOMETHING TO CELEBRATE WITH." A COPY OF THIS NOTE WILL BE INCLUDED WITH THIS REPORT.  JEFF RELEASED THE BOX AND PLACED IT IN THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY FOR FAA INVESTIGATION. THE CLINTON COUNTY SHERRIFS DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED.  OFFICER MICHAEL KASSINOS CAME TO AIRBORNE EXPRESS HAZMAT DEPT TO INSPECT THIS SHIPMENT.  OFFICER TIM SMITH FROM CLINTON COUNTY SHERRIFS DEPT CONTACTED AIRBORNE EXPRESS ON APRIL 18, 1997 AND ADVISED HE HAD CONTACTED THE DEPT OF ALCOHOL, TOBACCO AND FIREMARMS IN REGARDS TO THIS SHIPMENT, ON APRIL 19, 1997.  OFFICER TIM SMITH CONTACTED AIRBORNE EXPRESS HAZMAT DEPT AND SPOKE TO HAZMAT COORDINATOR BEN TAYLOR.  TIM ADVISED THE ATF DID NOT WANT TO PURSUE THIS SHIPMENT.  THIS SHIPMENT WILL REMAIN UNDER LOCK AND KEY UNTIL INVESTIGATED AND RELEASED BY THE FAA.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR OTHER ATTACHMENTS ON THE OUTSIDE OF THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS ARE A REGULATED MATERIAL.

FEDRICK DROVE TO THAT LOCATION AND FOUND TANK CAR ACFX78998 WITH A SMALL AMOUNT OF DRIED PRODUCT ON THE SIDE OF THE CAR.  THE SPILL APPEARED TO HAVE COME FROM THE MANWAY COVER.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE EIGHT MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE BARELY FINGER TIGHT.  ALL BOLTS WERE SECURED, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  NO PRODUCT REACHED THE GROUND.  THE LOUISANA STATE POLICE HAZMAT TEAM WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE INCIDENT.  CASE NUMBER 97-1796 WAS ASSIGNED TO THE INCIDENT, HOWEVER, FEDRICK WAS ADVISED THAT NO STATE OFFICERS WOULD COME TO THE SCENE.  SHIPPER REP TONY THIGPEN WAS ALSO NOTIFIED ABOUT THE INCIDENT.

column168: ON APRIL 30, 1997, SORT SUPERVISOR GARY LEE CALLED AND REPORTED THAT THERE WAS A LEAKING SHIPMENT HE BELIEVED TO BE A YELLOW PAINT AND THAT IT HAD A STRONG ODOR. HE FURTHER REPORTED THAT IT WAS DRYING VERY QUICKLY AND THAT IT CAME FROM UP IN SECONDARY 4 OF "B" BUILDING AND SEVERAL EMPLOYEES HAD BEEN IN CONTACT BY INHALATION, BUT THAT NO ONE WAS EXPERIENCE ANY RESPITORY DIFFICULTIES OR NAUSEA, THUS NO ACCIDENT OR WORKERS COMPENSATION REPORTS WERE FILED, AND NO TIME WAS LOST DUE TO THIS INCIDENT. UPON ARRIVAL, THE AREA HAS BEEN EVACUATED AND SPILL TECHNICIAN, WAYNE HOGSETT DONNED AN AIR PURIFYING CARTRIDGE MASK, AND NOTED THE FOLLOWING. THE DIMS ARE 10"X6"X14.5". THE TOP OF THE FIBERBOARD BOX WAS MARKED WITH THE WORD "TOP" AND ON EACH END WERE TWO ARROWS POINING IN THE DIRECTION OF THE TOP OF THE PACKAGE. ON EACH SIDE OF THE BOX WERE THE FOLLOWING MARKINGS AS SHOWN HERE. ICI AUTOCOLOR - CAR COLOUR SYSTEM - NORTH AMERICAN - MOTOR MANUFACTURED ALL OTHER MARKINGS BELOW THIS ON BOTH SIDES ARE ILLEGIBLE TO THE AMOUNT OF PAINT THAT LEAKED AND EVERYTHING ELSE, INCLUDING ON THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX. UPON VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS 6X1 QUART EACH METAL CAN. ONE OF THE CANS HAD LEAKED COMPLETELY AND TWO OTHERS ONLY PARTIALLY FOR AN APPROXIMATE TOTAL OF TWO QUARTS LOST. THE MANUFACTURER OF THE PAINT IS (ICI AUTOCOLOR) THE PAINT IS CALLED "2K P426-PP09 GOLD PEARL" THERE WERE NO INDICATION OF WHAT THE HAZARDOUS INGREDIENTS INDICATED ON THE MANUFACTURES WARNING LABEL. THE MANUFACTURE STATES THAT THE "MSDS" MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET BE CONSULTED BEFORE USING THE PRODUCT. SPILL TECHNICIAN WAYNE HOGSETT THEN BAGGED THE SHIPMENT AND PLACED IT IN OUR FLAMMABLE LIQUID CABINET UNDER LOCK AND KEY UNTIL IT COULD BE INVESTIGATED BY THE FAA HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AGENTS. UPON RELEASED THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED OR RETURNED BY REQUEST OF THE SHIPPER ACCORDING TO ALL APPLICABLE REGUALTIONS SET FORTH BY DOT 49CFR.
PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED AT HAZMAT CAGE 1 OF 1 ONE GALLON CONTAINERS' HAD A BROKEN SEAM. CONTENTS WAS REPOURED AND RTS'D DAMAGED WAS PROCESSED FOLLOWING PROPER DAMAGE PACKAGE PROCEDURE.

I RESPONDED TO OUTBOUND 7 BAY 930 FOR A HAZARDOUS SPILL.  I USED MY DECISION TREE WHICH LED ME TO MY CORROSIVE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEETS.  I USED CLAY BASED ABSORBENT TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL TO A PH LEVEL OF 7.  PROCESSED DAMAGED THRU DMP.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY THE DENVER NOTIFICATION CENTER, ADVISING THE SUPERVISOR YARD OPERATIONS, YERMO, CALIFORNIA, HAD REPORTED A LEAKING TANK CAR. MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED FRANK VALDEZ, SYO, YERMO, WHO ADVISED THE WEST END SWITCH CREW OBSERVED THE CAR LEAKING FROM THE TOP PORTION WHILE IT WAS BEING HANDLED DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS. AS THE CAR WAS PLACARDED CORROSIVE, IT WAS PLACED TO THE CAB TRACK WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO FACILITY, INSPECTED THE TANK CAR, AND NOTED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM A BURST FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT. THE SAFETY VENT, A STANDARD MIDLAND ASSEMBLY WITH BAFFLE, WHICH IS MOUNTED OUTSIDE THE WORK PLATFORM AREA, WAS DISASSEMBLED AND THE BURST DISC REPLACED WITH A LIKE TYPE 100 POUND BS&B STAINLESS/TEFLON FRANGIBLE DISC. THE SAFETY VENT WAS REASSEMBLED, THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS INSPECTED, AND FOUND TO BE PROPERLY SECURED. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT AND TYPE OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER AS INFORMATION.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Abrasion; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY AMERICAN PRESIDENT LINES PERSONNEL LOCATED IN THE UNION PACIFIC INTERMODAL FACILITY, LOS ANGELES, CALIFORNIA, WHO REPORTED A CONTAINER LEAKING.  AN OUTSIDE DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO PICK UP THE CONTAINER FOR DELIVERY WHEN HE OBSERVED AN UNKNOWN SUBSTANCE LEAKING THROUGH THE REAR DOORS.  HE LEFT THE CONTAINER AND NOTIFIED APL OF THE LEAKING CONDITION.  AS THE CONTAINER WAS PLACARDED FLAMMABLE GAS, IT WAS MOVED TO TRAILER STORAGE LOT #6 AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE INTERMODAL FACILITY AND OBSERVED A DARK LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE RIGHT REAR DOOR.  THE CONTAINER WAS ONLY PLACARDED FLAMMABLE GAS, HOWEVER THE WAY BILL INFORMATION ALSO LISTED ADDITIONAL CONTENTS AS NONFLAMMABLE GAS.  REAR DOOR SEALS, APL-SOK 537777 AND RHP 3504, WERE REMOVED IN  ORDER TO OPEN THE REAR DOORS FOR INSPECTION.  3 EACH 2X4'S WERE PLACED ACROSS THE REAR OF THE LADING IN A 'Z' PATTERN, IN AN EFFORT TO HOLD AN UPRIGHT PALLET IN PLACE TO SECURE THE LADING.  4 EACH 55 GALLON DRUMS WERE ACROSS THE REAR OF THE LOAD WITH PALLETS OF ADDITIONAL FREIGHT STACKED ON TOP OF THEM WITH NO BI-LEVEL SEPARATION.  THIS IS NOT A RECOMMENDED METHOD NOR IS IT APPROVED FOR THE BLOCKING AND BRACING, OR LOAD SEGREGATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DURING TRANSPORTATION PER THE AAR BOE 6C.  THE  MAJORITY OF THE LADING CONSISTED OF GENERAL FREIGHT, HOWEVER, UPON INSPECTION OF THE DRUMS ACROSS THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER, DEVELOPED THE CONTENTS TO BE A FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS N.0.S., TECHNICAL NAME, LUBE WELL HRL HOT ROLLING COMPOUND.  THIS COMMODITY WAS NOT LISTED ON THE SHIPPING PAPERS PROVIDED BY APL,  AND APPEARS TO HAVE NOT BEEN DECLARED BY THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER.  ONE OF THE DRUMS LOCATED AGAINST THE RIGHT SIDE WALL SUSTAINED DAMAGE TO THE LOWER ROLLING HOOP AND WAS SEEPING PRODUCT.  LESS THAN 5 GALLONS WAS LOST FROM THE DRUM.  THE DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO A OVERPACK FOR SECUREMENT.  AN ADDITIONAL DRUM ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE CONTAINER SUSTAINED HEAVY DAMAGE AND WAS DEEMED UNFIT FOR FURTHER TRANSPORT.  IT WAS ALSO PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK.  AS THERE WAS NO LOAD SEGREGATION AND LESS THAN ADEQUATE BLOCKING AND BRACING, BOTH OF THE DRUMS HAD SUSTAINED DAMAGE FROM THE ADJACENT FREIGHT SHIFTING DURING TRANSIT.  THE REMAINING LISTED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WERE LOCATED, AND AS THE FREIGHT WAS BEING PLACED BACK INTO THE CONTAINER, ALL OF THE HAZARDOUS COMMODITIES WERE SEGREGATED AT THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER.  THE CONTAINER WAS SECURED FOR MOVEMENT OVER THE ROAD TO A LOCAL WAREHOUSE WHERE THE CONTENTS WERE TO BE BROKEN DOWN FOR VARIOUS EXPORT LOCATIONS.  APL CORRECTED THE BILLING INFORMATION TO REFLECT THE ADDITIONAL COMMODITIES.  THE 2 DAMAGED DRUMS WERE DELIVERED SEPARATELY TO THE WAREHOUSE PENDING INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE SHIPPER FOR THEIR DISPOSITION.  DUE TO THE TYPE AND MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column60: Punctured; Abraded; Cracked; Crushed; Ripped or Torn
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY LATC RAMP MANAGER, ROBERT MCDOUGAL, WHO REPORTED A CONTAINER LEAKING.  THE CONTAINER WAS BEING REMOVED FROM AN INBOUND (WESTBOUND) TRAIN WHEN PRODUCT WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM THE REAR DOORS.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE LATC AND LOCATED THE CONTAINER TRACKSIDE, WHERE A CLEAR LIQUID WAS OBSERVED LEAKING THROUGH THE REAR DOORS A RATE OF 2-3 DRIPS PER MINUTE. THE LIQUID WAS FIELD TESTED FOR FLAMMABILITY AND FOUND TO BURN. AT THIS POINT, THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER WAS DIAPERED FOR MOVEMENT TO THE FREIGHT DOCK, WHERE THE DOORS COULD BE OPENED TO INSPECT THE LADING. ENVIRONMENTAL TRANSLOADING SERVICES, THE RAILROADS HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CONTRACTOR CLEANED THE RAILCAR AND THE TRACKSIDE PAVEMENT AREA, THEN PREPPED THE DOCK TO THE INSPECT THE CONTAINER.  UPON REMOVING SEAL BTTATL 187, THE REAR DOORS WERE OPENED AND NO BLOCKING OR BRACING WAS FOUND IN THE CONTAINER.  THE ENTIRE CONTENTS AT THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER HAD SHIFTED, AND THE LADING THAT HAD BEEN DOUBLE STACKED NEAR THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER HAD ALL TOPPLED TO THE REAR AS THERE WAS A 4-5 FOOT VOID WITH NO VISIBLE SUPPORT TO PREVENT MOVEMENT.  SEVERAL 5 GALLON PAILS CONTAINING THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID, N.O.S., TOPPLED TO THE REAR, BEING PUSHED AND CRUSHED BY THE FORWARD FREIGHT MOVING TO THE REAR.  A TOTAL OF 36 PAILS HAD BEEN STACKED ON THE FLOOR LOADED PALLET, 3 OF WHICH LOST THEIR ENTIRE CONTENTS, 12 OF WHICH HAD VARIOUS DEGREES OF DAMAGE THAT CAUSED MINOR LEAKS OF LESS THAN 1 PINT, AND 13 OF WHICH THAT WERE SO BADLY DAMAGED THAT THEY WERE DEEMED UNSUITABLE FOR FURTHER TRANSPORT, EVEN THOUGH THEY DID NOT LEAK.  ALL OF THE DAMAGED AND LEAKING PAILS WERE PLACED INTO OVERPACK DRUMS.  THERE WERE 5 EACH 55 GALLON DRUMS AT THE REAR DOORS THAT HAD BEEN FLOOR LOADED, EACH CONTAINING A FLAVORING EXTRACT THAT WAS LABELED FLAMMABLE.  EACH OF THESE DRUMS WERE SO COMPRESSED FROM THE LOAD SHIFT THAT THEY WERE FLAT ON ONE SIDE. AS THESE DRUMS WERE UNFIT FOR TRANSIT, THEY WERE PLACED INTO OVERPACKS, EVEN THOUGH THEY DID NOT LEAK.  FORWARD OF THE ABOVE FLAMMABLE DRUMS, WERE 10 DRUMS CONTAINING THE CORROSIVE LIQUID, N.O.S., 1 OF WHICH WAS DAMAGED AT THE UPPER ROLLING HOOP. RESULTING IN LESS THAN 1 GALLON OF PRODUCT TO BRE RELEASED.  THE ROLLING HOOP HAD ABRADED AGAINST AN ADJACENT DRUM ROLLING HOOP, WHICH WORE THE METAL TO THE POINT OF THINNING AND ALLOWED PRODUCT TO WEEP THROUGH.  ANOTHER DRUM OF THE SAME COMMODITY WAS WORN THROUGH AT THE LOWER ROLLING HOOP, RESULTING IN LESS THAN 1 GALLON OF PRODUCT BEING RELEASED. THIS DRUM WAS ALSO ABRADED FROM AN ADJACENT DRUM ROLLING HOOP THAT THINNED THE METAL AND ALLOWED PRODUCT TO WEEP THROUGH. IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT THE SHIPPER DID NOT USE ANY SEGREGATION OR BI-LEVEL SEPARATION REQUIRED BY AAR BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES PAMPHLET 6C FOR THE TRANSPORTATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THE FACT THAT THERE WAS NO BLOCKING OR BRACING WOULD INDICATE THE SHIPPER HAS NO CLUE TO THE REQUIREMENTS OF THE DEPARTMENT OF TRA

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Abrasion; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY THE SECURITY SUPERVISOR, ICTF INTERMODAL FACILITY, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA, REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER.  THE CONTAINER WAS INBOUND LANE #15 ATTEMPTING TO BE CHECKED OUT OF FACILITY.  APPARENTLY THE CONTAINER WAS MISSING A SEAL FROM THE REAR DOORS, AND WHEN THE DRIVER OPENED THE DOOR FOR THE GATE CLERK TO INSPECT THE LADING, ROUGHLY 100 POUNDS OF THE PRODUCT SPILL ONTO THE DRIVE AREA.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE INTERMODAL FACILITY AND FOUND THE CONTAINER PARKED IN THE OUTBOUND LANE WITH THE TRUCK AND DRIVER MISSING.  THE CLERK ADVISED AS SOON AS THE PRODUCT SPILLED FROM THE CONTAINER, THE DRIVER DISCONNECTED FROM THE CONTAINER AND LEFT THE PROPERTY.  TRAFFIC WAS DIVERTED AROUND THE OUTBOUND LANES TO PREVENT SPREADING OF THE GRANULATED MATERIAL.  ENVIRONMENTAL TRANSLOADING SERVICES, THE RAILROADS HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CONTRACTOR, ARRIVED AND BEGAN TO DRUM THE SPILLED MATERIAL.  ONCE THE BAG WAS PATCHED TO PREVENT ADDITIONAL SPILLAGE, THE DOORS WERE SECURED, AND THE CONTAINER MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK FOR FURTHER INSPECTION AND CONTAINMENT, AFTER ALL OF THE PRODUCT WAS REMOVED FROM THE ROADWAY, THE OUTBOUND GATES WERE REOPENED. INSPECTION AT THE DOCK DEVELOPED THE DRY GRANULATED PRODUCT WAS PLACED INTO 'SUPER SACKS', WHICH WERE DOUBLE STACKED ON A PALLET, WITH 2 PALLETS ACROSS THE REAR DOOR OF THE CONTAINER.  A BULK HEAD CONSTRUCTED OF 2X6 LUMBER WAS ACROSS THE REAR DOORS OF THE CONTAINER.  THE FABRIC 'SUPER SACKS' HAD ABRADED AGAINST THE LUMBER, WHICH TORE THE SACKS OPEN, THUS ALLOWED THE PRODUCT TO ESCAPE.  THERE WAS NO PLYWOOD BETWEEN THE LUMBER AND THE SACKS TO PROVIDE A FLAT SURFACE FOR THE SACKS TO REST AGAINST.  THIS METHOD OF SECURING SUPER SACKS IS NOT RECOMMENDED, NOR IS IT AN APPROVED METHOD PER THE AAR BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES 6C FOR THE TRANSPORTATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  UPON REMOVING THE SACKS FOR THE REAR DOOR, DEVELOPED THE REST OF THE LOAD CONSISTED OF A SINGLE SACKS PLACED ON TOP OF PALLETS THAT WERE FLOOR LOADED 2 ACROSS. AN ADDITIONAL PALLETIZED SACK HAD BEEN PLACED ON TOP OF THE FLOOR LOADED SACKS, AND CENTERED ON EACH ROW, ALL THE WAY TO THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER, WHERE THEY WERE ONCE AGAIN DOUBLE STACKED ON FLOOR LOADED PALLETS.  DID BAGS HAD BEEN PLACED BETWEEN THE CENTERED DOUBLE STACKED SACKS AND THE SIDEWALLS TO PREVENT SHIFTING DURING TRANSIT. ALL OF THE DID BAGS HAD BURST FROM THE SACKS SHIFTING AGAINST THEM. THIS,  ALSO IS NOT A RECOMMENDED METHOD, NOR IS IT AN APPROVED METHOD PER THE AAR BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES PAMPHLET 6C FOR THE SECUREMENT OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DURING TRANSIT.  IN TOTAL, 4 EACH SUPER SACKS HAD TO BE OVERPACKED OR PLACED INTO REPLACEMENT SACKS DUE TO ABRASION DAMAGE TO THE ORIGINAL SACK.  ONCE ALL OF SACKS WERE REMOVED FROM THE CONTAINER, THE PRODUCT WAS REMOVED FROM THE FLOOR AND PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUM FOR SECUREMENT.  A TOTAL OF 3 DRUMS WERE USED TO CONTAIN THE PRODUCT. THE SACKS WERE THEN RELOADED INTO THE ORIGINAL WHERE TH
DOCK WORKER, LOLA MASSEY, PICKED UP A SKID IN FRONT OF DRUMS. WENT TO FAR IN AND PUNCTURED THE DRUM.

column168: TWO OF FOUR HOLE COVER SECUREMENT NUTS NOR TOOL TIGHT, GCTX 413146, APRIL 9, 1997, PHILADELPHIA DIVISION        DURING A ROUTINE RAIL CAR INSPECTION WITH MR. R BUNDY, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPECIALIST, FEDERAL RAILROAD ADMINISTRATION, (FRA) INSPECTION OF GCTX 413146 CONTAINING SULFURIC ACID, IN OUTBOUND TRAIN, PHYSICALLY INSPECTED.  MR. BUNDY NOTICED TWO OF FOUR FILL HOLE COVER SECUREMENT NUTS WERE NOT TOOL TIGHT.  A VERY SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL WAS NOTED WET AN APPROXIMATELY 2" WIDE x 3" LONG PORTION OF THE MANWAY NOZZLE.  FRA CONTACTED THE SHIPPER GENERAL CHEMICAL, WHO DISPATCHED TWO REPRESENTATIVES TO SECURE CAR, AND CLEAN WET AREA ON NOZZLE, PRIOR TO TRANSPORTATION.  TANK CAR RELEASED FOR DESTINATION.
